Same question: which practice, in the pictures,
do you think entails less risk?

83
00:06:17,200 --> 00:06:19,850
We have finally arrived in the waste area.

84
00:06:19,850 --> 00:06:24,960
A space that needs to be controlled and properly
equipped.

85
00:06:24,960 --> 00:06:29,940
Clearly there are some practices that are
not recommended and they can be extremely

86
00:06:29,940 --> 00:06:32,970
dangerous for the operators and the surrounding
community.

87
00:06:32,970 --> 00:06:37,030
The slow burning here is extremely unsafe.

88
00:06:37,030 --> 00:06:41,440
A dangerous exposure to dioxins.

89
00:06:41,440 --> 00:06:48,210
Maybe at this point, it is important to distinguish
between burning and incineration.

90
00:06:48,210 --> 00:06:54,110
Burning is a thermal oxidation of waste able
to produce a reduction of the volume but not

91
00:06:54,110 --> 00:06:57,030
is decontamination.

92
00:06:57,030 --> 00:07:02,610
Only when incineration conditions are reached,
we can talk about destruction of the pathogen

93
00:07:02,610 --> 00:07:04,020
load in the waste.

94
00:07:04,020 --> 00:07:11,320
Oxygen, air flow, temperature and retention
time they should be in the right mix to allow

95
00:07:11,320 --> 00:07:13,880
incineration to happen.

96
00:07:13,880 --> 00:07:20,400
I’d like to stress a point that often come
up.

97
00:07:20,400 --> 00:07:25,590
Medical Waste Management is often assimilated
with Incineration only.

98
00:07:25,590 --> 00:07:30,770
Sometimes building or providing a new incinerator
is seen as a kind of miracle solution that

99
00:07:30,770 --> 00:07:33,670
makes the all waste problem disappears.

100
00:07:33,670 --> 00:07:39,100
Unfortunately, an incinerator is only a step
of a whole.

101
00:07:39,100 --> 00:07:44,020
Actually, incineration should be limited as
much as possible, because it always comes

102
00:07:44,020 --> 00:07:46,310
with important negative effects.

103
00:07:46,310 --> 00:07:54,810
A comprehensive study on small scale incinerators
commissioned by WHO in 2004 proved the following

104
00:07:54,810 --> 00:07:58,840
conclusions:
Single chamber incinerators (what I often

105
00:07:58,840 --> 00:08:03,540
call pizza hoven) should be banned because
their emission level is not acceptable.

106
00:08:03,540 --> 00:08:09,120
They don’t reach incineration conditions.

107
00:08:09,120 --> 00:08:15,470
Double-chamber self combustion incinerators,
like this one, should be used only as a transitional

108
00:08:15,470 --> 00:08:16,470
solution.

109
00:08:16,470 --> 00:08:22,500
If chosen, the way they are operated is paramount
it can tilt the balance between the overall

110
00:08:22,500 --> 00:08:24,370
cost benefit analysis.

111
00:08:24,370 --> 00:08:29,750
The same machine is giving very different
results.

112
00:08:29,750 --> 00:08:36,260
More advanced technologies such as assisted
combustion double chambers incinerators or

113
00:08:36,260 --> 00:08:42,539
completely different technology, like small
autoclaving should be promoted as soon as

114
00:08:42,539 --> 00:08:49,050
the proper conditions of financial and technical
sustainability exist.

115
00:08:49,050 --> 00:08:56,750
Problem is that in many cases, these conditions
are very very difficult to meet.

116
00:08:56,750 --> 00:09:03,220
They should be evaluated on a case by case
basis.

